3.2 Check for missing data on Bushfires

You will now use some data wrangling commands to unearth what is going on with missing values. Dealing with missing values is important and sometimes complicated. What we want to make sure is that we understand why data is missing, and deal with it accordingly. For example, in some cases, missing data may be missing because the values actually dont exist, or it may just be a placeholder for 0. Therefore, it is very important to distinguish truly missing data from data that is just missing a value. Deleting all rows with some missing data can result in loss of useful information and give biased results.

Time to wield your detective lens and wrangle with the data:

Lets take a look at the missing values in the n_fires column that contains the number of recorded bushfires for each month.

In the code chunk below, first calculate the proportion of missing values for each year. As you learned in datacamp, you can do this by taking the dataset and group_by() year, summarize() the number of NAs for each year, mutate a new column called perc_NA that calculates the percentage of NAs in each year, and then arrange() by decreasing order based on percentage of missing bushfires. (Some of the code is already done for you)

We will take a look at the data using the print command

perc_missing_fires <- fires_raw %>% group_by(year) %>%
  summarize(total_na = sum(is.na(n_fires)),
            total_observations = n()) %>% # n() calculates total observations by group (in this case, year)
  mutate(perc_na = total_na/total_observations*100) %>%
  arrange(desc(perc_na))

print(perc_missing_fires)
## # A tibble: 30 x 4
##     year total_na total_observations perc_na

By glancing at the printed output, are there any years with 100% missing values? Luckily, we know the reason why. The data documentation tells us that the years the fires started getting recorded by satellite. Go to https://firms.modaps.eosdis.nasa.gov/download/, check the Temporal coverage for MODIS Collection 6 and explain when the coverage started.

Now, that we know the cause of the missingness, we can create a clean bushfires data by using filter() to remove years with 100 % missing bushfires data.

# first we need to know what years are completely missing
# you can subset using what you learnt in lab1 as displayed here
years_missing100 <- perc_missing_fires$year[perc_missing_fires$perc_na == 100]
## A tidyverse way of doing this is below: it is more readable
years_missing100 <- perc_missing_fires %>% filter(perc_na == 100) %>%
  .$year
# Now we can filter only those that are NOT in 100% missing years: remember filter() equates to subsetting.
# %in% is a very useful operator that tells you to whether year is "in" any of the values of years stored in the years_missing100 vector.
# Also, since the the "Australian Capital Territory" does not have many fires , we will remove that from analysis too.
fires_noNa <- fires_raw %>% filter(!(year %in% years_missing100)) %>%
  filter(state_name !="Australian Capital Territory")

## check if there are any more missing values
is.na(fires_noNa$n_fires) %>% sum() %>% cat("There are", ., "missing n_fires values")
## There are 97 missing n_fires values

** Arghhhhh, we are not done yet. There are still missing values, but the good news is that since we know the data was collected from 2003 onwards, these values show that no Bushfires were detected during the missing value months. Let’s replace the remaining NAs with 0.

# The tidyr package in tidyverse has a handy replace_NA function
fires_noNa$n_fires <- fires_noNa$n_fires %>% replace_na(0)
  
## check if there are any more missing values
is.na(fires_noNa$n_fires) %>% sum() %>% cat("There are", ., "missing n_fires values")
## There are 0 missing n_fires values

Woohoo! no more missing values, we are all set to move to the fun part: Explorations and Visualizations and Visualizations

3.4 Visualize Bushfires

3.4.1 Histograms of Bushfires

In summary, histograms visualize how your data is distributed. and help you understand the shape of your data distribution. We will cover them in detail in later lectures, but for now, take a look at the graph below:

fires_noNa %>% ggplot() + 
  geom_histogram(aes(x = n_fires), binwidth = 100, col = "white") + 
  xlab("Number of fires") + 
  ggtitle("Distribution of All fires across Australia") +
  theme_bw()

The graph does not really tell us much except that the majority of months have low or no bushfires. However, there are certain months that have a large number of fires, with some having as many as 10000 fires. (The outliers are not clear visually in the graph, but they do exist)

Next, we can easily view this histograms for each state in a nice comparable graph using the facet_wrap() function as shown below.

fires_noNa %>% ggplot() + 
  geom_histogram(aes(x = n_fires), col = "white") + facet_wrap(~state_name) +
  xlab("Number of fires") +
  theme_bw()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

We notice that the histograms differ a bit by state, but not to a large extent.

Using the histogram can you deduce which state might have more severe fires as compared with another? 3.4.2 Bar Plots

Now, lets try plotting Bar plots

The amazing part about piping is that you can transform your data on the fly and feed it to the ggplot() using piping. Dont worry, this lab will not test you on that, but this is something useful to know for later.

fires_noNa %>% group_by(year) %>% 
  summarize(n_fires = sum(n_fires)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>%
  ggplot() + 
  geom_bar(aes(x = year,y=n_fires), stat="identity", col = "white") + 
  xlab("Number of fires") +
  theme_bw()

fires_noNa %>% group_by(state_name,year) %>% 
  summarize(n_fires = sum(n_fires)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>%
  ggplot() + 
  geom_bar(aes(x = year,y=n_fires), stat="identity", col = "white") + 
  facet_wrap(~state_name) +
  xlab("Number of fires") +
  theme_bw()

fires_noNa %>% group_by(state_name,month) %>% 
  summarize(n_fires = sum(n_fires)) %>%
